1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:01,840
Now, once we have a tokenizer,

2

00:00:01,840  -->  00:00:05,995
we will look into how to handle datasets in PyTorch.

3

00:00:05,995  -->  00:00:11,915
There are two types that PyTorch provides for us to work with datasets.

4

00:00:11,915  -->  00:00:17,870
Dataset is a class that allows loading and processing data.

5

00:00:17,870  -->  00:00:25,330
Data loader is a class that allows us to iterate over samples in a PyTorch dataset.

6

00:00:25,330  -->  00:00:28,470
Let's look into these types one by one.

7

00:00:28,470  -->  00:00:30,210
To define a dataset,

8

00:00:30,210  -->  00:00:33,830
we first need to define a new class that inherits from

9

00:00:33,830  -->  00:00:38,885
the dataset class that we import from the torch.utils.data.

10

00:00:38,885  -->  00:00:44,050
As an example, let's see how we can implement a dataset that stores

11

00:00:44,050  -->  00:00:49,750
a list of samples and allows to perform arbitrary transformations on that.

12

00:00:49,750  -->  00:00:51,950
To implement a dataset,

13

00:00:51,950  -->  00:00:54,890
we need to implement three methods.

14

00:00:54,890  -->  00:00:58,710
A constructor that receives arbitrary parameters.

15

00:00:58,710  -->  00:01:01,530
In this case, we have two parameters,

16

00:01:01,530  -->  00:01:06,020
data to store and a transformation to apply.

17

00:01:06,020  -->  00:01:09,870
The second method that we need to implement is len

18

00:01:09,870  -->  00:01:14,005
that returns a number of elements in the dataset.

19

00:01:14,005  -->  00:01:18,860
The final method we need to implement is get item that returns

20

00:01:18,860  -->  00:01:24,160
an item from the provided position that is passed as the index parameter.

21

00:01:24,160  -->  00:01:26,060
In this particular example,

22

00:01:26,060  -->  00:01:32,940
our dataset receives a list of samples and a function to transform each sample.

23

00:01:32,940  -->  00:01:35,920
The implementation of the len method just

24

00:01:35,920  -->  00:01:39,400
needs to return the number of samples in the list.

25

00:01:39,400  -->  00:01:41,380
In the getitem method,

26

00:01:41,380  -->  00:01:44,960
we need to get a sample with the provided index,

27

00:01:44,960  -->  00:01:49,550
apply transformation, and return the transformed result.

28

00:01:49,550  -->  00:01:52,220
This is, of course, a very simple dataset,

29

00:01:52,220  -->  00:01:54,360
but they can be arbitrary complex,

30

00:01:54,360  -->  00:01:57,285
they can low data from external storage,

31

00:01:57,285  -->  00:02:00,520
apply complex transformations, and so on.

32

00:02:00,520  -->  00:02:04,280
Here's how we could use our dataset implementation.

33

00:02:04,280  -->  00:02:07,860
Let's say we have a dataset of images.

34

00:02:07,860  -->  00:02:13,995
To use it, we can create an instance of the custom dataset class we've just implemented,

35

00:02:13,995  -->  00:02:15,880
pass a list of images,

36

00:02:15,880  -->  00:02:20,800
and a function to transform each image before returning it.

37

00:02:20,800  -->  00:02:24,000
In this case, we provide a function that resizes

38

00:02:24,000  -->  00:02:28,145
each image before we get it from a dataset.

39

00:02:28,145  -->  00:02:35,430
Having this class, we can get a number of samples in our dataset using the len function,

40

00:02:35,430  -->  00:02:40,430
or we can get an image from a certain position in this dataset.

41

00:02:40,430  -->  00:02:45,130
Additionally, we can iterate over samples in our dataset.

42

00:02:45,130  -->  00:02:47,770
However, when training a model,

43

00:02:47,770  -->  00:02:52,630
we usually don't use a single sample on every training iteration.

44

00:02:52,630  -->  00:02:58,350
Using a single sample at a time is called stochastic gradient descent,

45

00:02:58,350  -->  00:03:03,615
and it does not allow us to utilize resources in an efficient way.

46

00:03:03,615  -->  00:03:07,120
The other issue is that the training loss will also

47

00:03:07,120  -->  00:03:10,800
fluctuate greatly from one iteration to the other.

48

00:03:10,800  -->  00:03:15,720
We want to use multiple examples on every training iteration.

49

00:03:15,720  -->  00:03:22,000
Using the whole dataset on every iteration is called batch gradient descent.

50

00:03:22,000  -->  00:03:25,340
But it is impractical in many cases.

51

00:03:25,340  -->  00:03:32,180
Using the whole dataset is computationally expensive and will require a lot of memory.

52

00:03:32,180  -->  00:03:34,630
Instead, in most cases,

53

00:03:34,630  -->  00:03:38,570
models are trained using so called mini batches.

54

00:03:38,570  -->  00:03:41,250
When on every training iteration,

55

00:03:41,250  -->  00:03:48,210
we would use a small subset of training samples and train our model using this subset.

56

00:03:48,210  -->  00:03:53,810
Each subset of samples used on a single iteration is called a mini-batch.

57

00:03:53,810  -->  00:03:57,110
Using mini-batches is more manageable than using

58

00:03:57,110  -->  00:04:00,900
a whole data set and leads to better results.

59

00:04:00,900  -->  00:04:05,150
It also allows to utilize resources more efficiently,

60

00:04:05,150  -->  00:04:10,210
allowing to train our model on multiple samples on every iteration.

61

00:04:10,210  -->  00:04:13,790
To iterate other mini-batches from our dataset,

62

00:04:13,790  -->  00:04:17,425
we need to use another type called DataLoader.

63

00:04:17,425  -->  00:04:21,870
Here is how DataLoader and dataset types are used.

64

00:04:21,870  -->  00:04:27,870
We first need to create an instance of a dataset to provide access to our data.

65

00:04:27,870  -->  00:04:34,115
We then need to create an instance of DataLoader to iterate over the training data.

66

00:04:34,115  -->  00:04:38,260
Then the training code can use DataLoader instance

67

00:04:38,260  -->  00:04:42,730
to load a patch of data at a time and use it for training.

68

00:04:42,730  -->  00:04:46,845
We don't need to implement a custom type to use a DataLoader.

69

00:04:46,845  -->  00:04:50,280
We need to create an instance of the DataLoader type,

70

00:04:50,280  -->  00:04:54,700
pass our dataset, and the size of a batch it should return.

71

00:04:54,700  -->  00:05:01,580
Then we can iterate over the DataLoader instance to get our data split into batches.

72

00:05:01,580  -->  00:05:03,960
On every iteration of the sloop,

73

00:05:03,960  -->  00:05:07,480
the data variable will contain 64 elements

74

00:05:07,480  -->  00:05:12,740
from the custom dataset that we can now use to train our model.
